Notation: <br>
<font color = 'green'>sage:</font color> 'What we enter into sage' (note, we do not enter the 'sage:' part) <br>
>>> <font color = 'blue'>'The result that is returned by sage'</font color> <br>
<br>
To calculate The vector projection of the left vector onto the right vector in sage, we type; <br>
<font color = 'green'>sage:</font color> (vecLeft.dot_product(vecRight)/(vecRight.norm())^2) * vecRight <br>
Where ‘vecLeft and vecRight’ are the vectors you have previously defined (see 'How do I enter a vector in sage' above).<br>
To break this down a bit; <br>
<font color = 'green'>sage:</font color> a = vecLeft.dot_product(vecRight) <br>
<font color = 'green'>sage:</font color> b = vecRight.norm() <br>
<font color = 'green'>sage:</font color> c = a / b^2 <br>
<font color = 'green'>sage:</font color> c * vecRight <br>
>>> <font color = 'blue'>(1/14*sqrt(14), 1/7*sqrt(14), 3/14*sqrt(14))</font color>
